<div class="col-md-6">
<p>Packing a kitchen for a move may seem like a daunting task, even after going through the process of researching the <a >best moving companies</a>. Not only do you have large appliances and dishes to consider, but there’s also the factor of perishable food. Additionally, kitchen items tend to be dissimilar in size and shape, making it difficult to determine what types of boxes and other moving supplies will work best. Knowing how to pack kitchen items will save you time, energy and headaches. Follow this systematic approach when packing up your kitchen for moving.</p>
</div>
</div>
<br>
<br>
<h4>Gather Supplies</h4>
<p>The right supplies will make a big difference when it comes to packing a kitchen. You will need a variety of boxes and protective materials for dishes and other breakables.</p>
<h4>Boxes</h4>
<p>Gather a variety of large, medium and small boxes. Large boxes are best for lightweight and odd-shaped items such as small appliances, bakeware, plastic storage containers, dish racks, etc. Medium boxes work best for heavier items like cookbooks and dishes. Boxes with handles make it easier to lift and move. Heavy-duty boxes are perfect for breakables like glassware.</p>
<h4>Packing Paper</h4>
<p>Packing paper is typically unprinted newsprint sold in sheets. It’s used to wrap fragile items to  help prevent them from breaking during storage or moving.</p>
<h4>Bubble Wrap</h4>
<p>Like packing paper, bubble wrap is used for protecting fragile items. Bubble wrap is more expensive than packing paper, so only use it on especially fragile items.</p>
<h4>Glass Dividers</h4>
<p>Dividers are useful for packing stemware and glasses. They can also be used to store vases or other fragile items. Glass dividers come in several sizes to accommodate different boxes.</p>
<h4>Packing Tape</h4>
<p>Use a good quality packing tape and dispenser. You will be using a lot of it, so consider purchasing it in bulk.</p>
<h4>Markers</h4>
<p>Use a dark colored marker to label boxes. Labeling will help keep you organized and help you remember what’s in the box. With your labeling include what is in the box, and be sure to add “fragile” if applicable.</p>
<h4>Declutter</h4>
<p>Before packing a room, start with decluttering. There is no point in packing an item that you no longer use and do not plan to use in your new home. Go through every cabinet and drawer. Toss anything that is damaged and donate gently used items you no longer want or need.</p>
<h4>Make an Essentials Box</h4>
<p>You will need some kitchen essentials after the movers leave and when you arrive in your new home. Pack those items in a separate box and label them clearly so you can identify them and prevent them from getting mixed up with your other boxes. Some items to put in your essential box include a few dishes, cutlery, food items and perhaps a coffee maker.</p>
<h4>Pack Less Used Items First</h4>
<p>Items you use the least should get packed first. These items can include specialty appliances, formal <a href="https://www.forbes.com/home-improvement/moving-services/how-to-pack-glasses-dishes/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><span style="color: #ff7c64;">dinnerware and glasses</span></a>, seasonal items, cookbooks, small appliances, pictures and decorative accessories. Small, miscellaneous items drawers can be packed along with less frequently used items as well. You can start packing these items weeks before the movers arrive.</p>
<p>Dishes are heavy and fragile, so a medium-sized, heavy-duty box is best. Place a double layer of bubble wrap on the bottom of the box. Wrap each plate and bowl with a sheet of packing paper. Lay the dishes in one at a time, starting with the dinner plates. Add an additional layer of bubble wrap every three dishes or so. Place the smaller pieces on top and nest the bowls into each other. Fill any negative space with extra packing paper.<br />
<div id="cta-builder" class="cta-builder exclude-eds with-map" data-mktp-container='{"componentTitle":"Get Your Free Moving Estimate","componentType":"CTA Builder"}'>
	

</p>
<h4>Glassware and Mugs</h4>
<p>Insert a glass divider into a medium-sized box. Wrap each glass or mug with a sheet of packing paper and insert them into the dividers. You can place vases or other narrow, fragile items into the dividers as well. Add a layer of bubble wrap on top of glasses for added security before you tape the box shut. This step will help protect the glassware just in case something heavy gets placed on top of the box.</p>
<h4>Flatware and Utensils</h4>
<p>The quickest and easiest way to pack flatware is to wrap plastic around the tray and then place it flat inside of a box. For other serving utensils, group them in like sizes and place them into large zip baggies or wrap them in plastic wrap before placing them into the box. For sharp knives, wrap them in packing paper individually, then wrap them in a kitchen towel. Place them faced down in the box.<br />
